From 1210f230aa7506e1583ca888361c1f8dd666ea60 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 08:23:02 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 6/6] selftests/membarrier: Add tests for
 MEMBARRIER_CMD_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ

Exercise the shared RSEQ fence:

  - Argument and permission validation: unregistered callers get EPERM;
    private, read only or unmapped addresses and non zero flags get
    EINVAL.

  - A registered process spinning in an RSEQ critical section on a
    shared writable page is aborted by a fence on that page issued by
    another process.

  - A process which did not register is not disturbed, even though it
    maps the page. As every RSEQ event aborts the spinner, background
    preemption noise is filtered by comparing against a fence free
    control phase.

  - A registered process which does not map the fenced page is not
    disturbed.

This series was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>

squash! selftests/membarrier: Add tests for MEMBARRIER_CMD_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ

Gate the build on x86-64 (issue #29): the RSEQ spin loop is x86-64
assembly, and the generic membarrier Makefile is built on every
architecture.

Make the positive fence test unable to pass without fencing (issue
30): aborts observed before the first fence (startup preemptions or
migrations) are discarded, at least one fence is always issued, and
only an abort observed after a fence satisfies the test.
